Why do I toe
that razor-ridged line
that bars the sage-wise
from the bitter insane,

the polite from the gluttons,
profusely profane,
the aspirin from
the lingering pain?

'Cause in life's great spectrum,
I sit in the middle,
an ardent moderate
in my homely domain,

afraid not of questions
of sure certainty,
but burdened by relics
of what I can't see.

Why do I nourish my blood
with those sultry brown beans
from inelegant jungles,
honey-ripe with duress,

and yet criticize others
for their silver-strewn vice,
oblique but benign
in the realm of my mind?

Because qualms arbitrary
do make a good compass
that faithfully settles
wherever you please;

and steer you, they will,
when clouds block your stars
and your sextant is rendered
a polymath's toy.

Perhaps something greater
awaits my demise,
to lift my limp body
through ravenous skies;

or maybe the only lives
after this one
carry on in the minds
of the people I love.

So make your strange choices
and pick your fights blind,
for the missteps you take
are your essence defined.